egory, Black Hawk Hancock offers an embedded and embodied ethnography that situates dance within a larger Chicago landscape of segregated social practices. Delving into two Chicago dance worlds, the Lindy and Steppin’, Hancock uses a combination of participant-observation and interviews to bring to the surface the racial tension that surrounds white use of black cultural forms. Focusing on new forms of appropriation in an era of multiculturalism, Hancock underscores the institutionalization of racial disparities and offers wonderful insights into the intersection of race and culture in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericanszIllinoiszChicagoxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aBlacksxRace identityzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aChicago (Ill.)xRace relationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aDance and race. 0aLindy (Dance)zIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aWhitesxRace identityzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226043241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226043241.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles